We can “derive” the tax‐payable balance by “summing” up the tax amounts that were charged on Sales (since in our data only sales carry a tax amount) and then noting that no “initial” payable existed. (In our sample data the “Initial… ” rows do not include any tax entries.) 

Step 1. Identify the “Sale” rows and read the “tax_amount” value for each (the column “tax_amount”). For example, the first sale row (“Sale20240102003”) has a tax of 686.41; the next “Sale20240103005” has 568.36; and so on.

If you add these one‐by‐one (or group–by–group) you obtain a final total of 129132.73.

Step 3. Because none of the “Initial” transactions had any tax (and we assume no beginning rollover tax payable exists) the “Taxes Payable Initial Value” equals 0.00; and then—the “final” taxes payable is the sum of all tax amounts recorded on Sales.
